<title>CANADA: Canada 1996 petroleum product sales rise 3.6 pct.</title>
<headline>Canada 1996 petroleum product sales rise 3.6 pct.</headline>
<dateline>OTTAWA 1997-02-03</dateline>
<text>
<p>Statistics Canada on Monday issued the following data for sales of refined petroleum products:</p>
<p>PETROLEUM PRODUCT SALES (thousands of cubic meters)</p>
<p>				     1996	   1995	    pct</p>
<p>   Total sales		 87,326.7     84,272.8	 +3.6</p>
<p>   Motor gasoline	    35,444.8     35,052.7	 +1.1</p>
<p>   Diesel fuel		 19,926.2     19,166.3	 +4.0</p>
<p>   Light fuel oil	     5,998.2	5,430.9	+10.4</p>
<p>   Heavy fuel oil	     6,134.9	6,416.4	 -4.4</p>
<p>   Aviation turbo fuels     5,618.3	5,036.2	+11.6</p>
<p>				     1996	   1995	    pct</p>
<p>   Petrochemical feedstocks 4,600.8	4,384.4	 +4.9</p>
<p>   All other products	 9,603.5	8,785.9	 +9.3</p>
<p>PETROLEUM PRODUCT SALES (thousands of cubic meters)</p>
<p>				    Dec 1996     Dec 1995	 pct</p>
<p>   Total sales		  7,284.9	7,412.7	 -1.7</p>
<p>   Motor gasoline	     2,842.1	2,930.2	 -3.0</p>
<p>   Diesel fuel		  1,549.6	1,596.8	 -3.0</p>
<p>   Light fuel oil		 670.3	  818.6	-18.1</p>
<p>   Heavy fuel oil		 750.6	  766.1	 -2.0</p>
<p>   Aviation turbo fuels	 454.4	  387.1	+17.4</p>
<p>   Petrochemical feedstocks   367.8	  335.1	 +9.8</p>
<p>   All other products	   650.1	  578.8	+12.3</p>
<p>It said strong sales of light fuel oil in the year were largely due to unseasonable cold in the first half and in October and November. Increased diesel fuel oil sales reflected higher demand by the transportation and crude oil and natural gas extraction industries.</p>
<p>Heavy fuel oil sales declined, mainly because of falling use by electrical utilities.</p>
<p>(For more information from Statistics Canada, contact David Roeske, Energy Section, (613) 951-3563.)</p>
<p>((Reuters Ottawa Bureau (613) 235-6745))</p>
